At 05:18 PM 6/11/2001 -0400, you wrote:&lt;br&gt;
&lt;blockquote type=cite cite&gt;Thanks for the example in design issues... but
that isn&#39;t what I was after.&lt;br&gt;
I should have been more clear, and I will be next 
time.&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Ok. Point well taken. back to the main track.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
&lt;blockquote type=cite cite&gt;&nbsp;I wanted to point out the potential
flaws of design and&lt;br&gt;
testing that could otherwise be missed when you put tests in the
same&lt;br&gt;
package as production code.&nbsp; The production code should be tested in
the&lt;br&gt;
same fashion it would be used by a client.&nbsp; A test is a client in
some&lt;br&gt;
degree.&nbsp; In most cases clients exist outside of the package. &lt;br&gt;
[..snip]&lt;br&gt;
Thus,&lt;br&gt;
I conclude, that testing the public interfaces of ALL objects (the key
being&lt;br&gt;
ALL) should prove sufficient, thus not needing the tests to reside in
the&lt;br&gt;
same package as their associated production code objects.&nbsp; Of
course, there&lt;br&gt;
are exceptions... we have ways around those.&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;
In an ideal world, you&#39;re right. Testing *all* the public methods should
give you complete functional coverage. &lt;br&gt;
However:&lt;br&gt;
1. You might want to put more stress on some classes and less on others.
In this case, you might want to test more then the public methods of
critical-path components, and less of the peripherals.&lt;br&gt;
2. You might want to access non-public methods in your setUp /
tearDown.&lt;br&gt;
3. Sometimes the tested class needs a sophisticated context in runtime
(EJB / Servlet). In this case, you might want to short circuit it in
testing by calling protected / default access methods that would be
called by the public interface in production mode.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
True, you might call all these &quot;exceptions&quot;. True, they deter
from the pure model. Still, they are common, and are easily resolved by
placing tests in the same package. On the other hand, I don&#39;t see the
actual harm of doing so.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
B.t.w., the right access mode for &quot;accessible in package only&quot;
is &quot;default&quot;. &quot;protected&quot; makes it accessible to both
package members and subclassses. &lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
- Yishay &lt;br&gt;

